An 1843 illustration, a quaint relic from a bygone era, depicts a [French](/First_French_Empire) aide-de-camp (positioned on the right, naturally) diligently assisting a [général de division](/Divisional_general) (in the opulent center) amidst the chaos of the [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars). A rather telling tableau, wouldn't you say?

An aide-de-camp, pronounced with that distinctly [UK](/British_English) [/ˌeɪddəˈkɒ̃/](/Help:IPA/English) lilt or the more abrupt [US](/American_English) [/-ˈkæmp/](/Help:IPA/English) (one simply must pick a side, apparently [1]), is a term borrowed directly from the [French language](/French_language). It rather literally translates to "helper in the [military camp](/Military_camp)" [2]. In practice, it refers to a [personal assistant](/Personal_assistant) or a [secretary](/Secretary) — though "secretary" often sounds far too mundane for the gravitas involved — who serves an individual of exceptionally high [rank](/Military_rank). This typically includes senior figures within the [military](/Officer_(armed_forces)), [police](/Police_officer) or [government officer) establishments, or even members of a [royal family](/Royal_family) or a [head of state](/Head_of_state). Their proximity to power is, by design, absolute.

These individuals aren't merely glorified assistants; an aide-de-camp may be called upon to participate in various [ceremonial](/Ceremony) functions, often serving as a highly visible extension of their principal. Indeed, the first aide-de-camp is generally considered the foremost personal aide, holding a position of significant trust and responsibility, despite the often public-facing nature of their duties. It's crucial, however, not to conflate this role with that of an [adjutant](/Adjutant), who typically functions as the senior administrator of a military unit, dealing with the nitty-gritty of internal operations rather than the personal affairs and public representation of a high-ranking officer.

The unmistakable badge of office for an aide-de-camp is usually the [aiguillette](/Aiguillette). This distinctive accessory, a braided cord often rendered in gleaming gold or other specific colors, is worn prominently on the shoulder of a uniform. Its placement, whether on the left or the right shoulder, is not a matter of personal preference, but rather rigidly dictated by established protocol, a testament to the meticulous nature of such appointments.

In a select few countries, the designation "aide-de-camp" transcends a mere job title; it is considered a [title of honour](/Title_of_honour). This esteemed appointment may confer the privilege of using the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) ADC or A de C, a subtle but clear indication of the individual's distinguished service and proximity to authority.

## Argentina

This particular section, much like a conversation started too early in the morning, also needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Should you feel compelled, please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Aide-de-camp) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Otherwise, this unsourced material may, predictably, be challenged and removed. Find sources: "Aide-de-camp" – news · newspapers · books · scholar · JSTOR (October 2022). One might also consider [Learning how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal).

In [Argentina](/Argentina), the system of aide-de-camp appointments is rather structured. Three officers, each drawn from a distinct branch of the armed services and holding the rank of lieutenant colonel (or its equivalent in the navy or air force), are specifically appointed as aide-de-camp to the [president of the republic](/President_of_Argentina). Similarly, another three officers, mirroring the same rank and service diversity, are appointed to the [minister of defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(Argentina)). These six individuals are the exclusive holders of the title *edecán*, which is the Spanish phonetic rendition of the French term "aide-de-camp." Alternatively, the more direct Spanish [calque](/Calque) *ayuda* or *ayudante de campo* exists, though *edecán* seems to be preferred for these particular high-level roles.

A minor kerfuffle arose in 2006, when then-president [Néstor Kirchner](/N%C3%A9stor_Kirchner) saw fit to promote his army aide-de-camp, Lieutenant Colonel Graham, to the rank of colonel a full year ahead of his peers. Such actions, while perhaps intended as a mark of favor, invariably ignite questions of meritocracy and influence. Following this, upon assuming the presidency, [Cristina Kirchner](/Cristina_Kirchner) made a notable departure from tradition by, for the first time in the nation's history, appointing female officers as her personal aides-de-camp, a move that undoubtedly garnered attention.

Beyond the presidential and ministerial echelons, within each of the armed forces, the chief of staff and other senior officers are typically assigned their own adjutants. These adjutants usually hold the rank of major or lieutenant colonel, or their equivalent. At the more granular unit level, the unit [S1](/S1_(military)) (the personnel officer) often doubles as the unit commander's adjutant. However, in contemporary practice, this dual role has largely been relegated to ceremonial occasions. For the more prosaic, everyday duties, a senior [non-commissioned officer](/Non-commissioned_officer) often takes on the practical responsibilities associated with the adjutant's activities, a sensible division of labor.

The aiguillette, that distinctive braided cord, is worn on the right shoulder by both aides-de-camp and adjutants in Argentina, serving as a clear visual symbol of their designated position. The color of this aiguillette is not arbitrary; it is carefully chosen to reflect the rank of the principal they are serving. One might observe golden, tan, silver, and red aiguillettes, each signifying a different level of authority, along with a more subdued olive-green version reserved for combat uniforms, because even in the field, distinctions must be maintained.

## Belgium

In [Belgium](/Belgium), the intricacies of royal and military support are well-defined. The individual holding the esteemed position of Head of the King's Military Household is typically a two, three, or even four-star General. This high-ranking officer serves as a crucial intermediary, assisting the King in fulfilling the constitutional powers vested in him concerning national defense. Their responsibilities are comprehensive: they meticulously monitor the international security landscape, providing the King with timely and relevant intelligence. Furthermore, they ensure the King remains thoroughly informed about the current status, capabilities, resources, operational effectiveness, and specific missions of the [Belgian Armed Forces](/Belgian_Armed_Forces), working in close collaboration with the King's Cabinet. The Head of the Military Household also shoulders the critical task of coordinating security arrangements for the Royal Palace and manages the entire Information Technology Service, an increasingly vital component of any modern command structure.

The Aides de Camp to the King occupy a distinct, though equally important, role. These are general or senior officers who are specifically assigned by the King to accompany important visitors of state or to represent him on occasions where his personal presence is not feasible. They are, in essence, the King's proxies, extending his presence and authority.

The Equerries to the King, by contrast, are in constant attendance, operating on a rotational basis. Their duties are more immediate and personal: they accompany the King on his travels, ensuring his needs are met, and provide direct assistance in the performance of his daily tasks [3]. Their role is one of continuous, intimate support.

The title of honorary aide-de-camp to the [King](/Monarchy_of_Belgium) is a distinction that can be bestowed by the royal court in recognition of exceptional services rendered. This is not a working appointment but a mark of royal favor. Notable individuals who have received this honor include Major General Baron [Édouard Empain](/%C3%89douard_Empain), Count Charles John d'Oultremont, and Lieutenant General Baron [Albert du Roy de Blicquy](/Albert_du_Roy_de_Blicquy), names that resonate with a certain historical prestige.

## Commonwealth of Nations countries

Ah, the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations). A collection of countries, many with shared histories under a particular crown. Here, the role of aides-de-camp often serves as a living, braided thread connecting military tradition with modern governance. In these nations, aides-de-camp are predominantly appointed from the ranks of their respective military or auxiliary services. Upon appointment, they are granted the privilege of appending the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) ADC or A de C after their names [4], a small but significant marker of their special status. The tangible emblem of this office, as is common elsewhere, remains the [aiguillette](/Aiguillette), that elaborate braided cord worn on their uniform, silently proclaiming their connection to higher authority.

### Australia

