In [Australia](/Australia), officers drawn from the [Australian Defence Force](/Australian_Defence_Force) are appointed to serve as aides-de-camp to a specific roster of senior appointments. This includes, rather predictably, the [monarch](/Monarchy_of_Australia) (though typically represented by the Governor-General), the [governor-general](/Governor-General_of_Australia) themselves, the various state governors, the [chief of the Defence Force](/Chief_of_the_Defence_Force_(Australia)), and other specifically designated command appointments within the Army, Navy, and Air Force. Those who serve as honorary aides-de-camp to the governor-general or state governors are granted the right to use the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) ADC for the duration of their appointment, a temporary badge of honor.

Officers holding the ranks of rear admiral, major general, and air vice-marshal, or higher, who are in specifically designated command appointments, are authorized to have an aide-de-camp. This aide usually holds the army rank of captain or its equivalent in the other services. Within the [Royal Australian Navy](/Royal_Australian_Navy) (RAN), an aide-de-camp is referred to as a "flag lieutenant," a term that hints at the maritime tradition. Senior naval officers, those commanding fleets or large formations, are themselves known as "[flag officers](/Flag_officer)," a title that underscores their authority and the presence of their command flag.

