In a grim reminder of the inherent risks associated with proximity to power, 1973 saw a tragic incident in [Bermuda](/Bermuda). [Sir Richard Sharples](/Richard_Sharples), who held the office of [governor of Bermuda](/Governor_of_Bermuda) at the time, and his aide-de-camp, Captain Hugh Sayers, were both brutally murdered on the very grounds of Government House. A stark testament to the fact that even ceremonial roles can carry the ultimate price.

### Canada

A rather telling photograph from 2006 captures Aide-de-camp Colonel Jean-Claude Cloutier standing with the [lieutenant-governor of Quebec](/Lieutenant-governor_of_Quebec), [Lise Thibault](/Lise_Thibault). Another image, equally illustrative of the meticulous details of rank and honor, displays [Royal Canadian Navy](/Royal_Canadian_Navy) shoulder boards, specifically those worn by honorary aides-de-camp to the lieutenant-governors of [British Columbia](/Lieutenant_Governor_of_British_Columbia) (on the left), [Quebec](/Lieutenant_Governor_of_Quebec) (in the center), and [New Brunswick](/Lieutenant_Governor_of_New_Brunswick) (on the right). Such visual cues are, apparently, essential.

In [Canada](/Canada), the appointment of aides-de-camp extends across a broad spectrum of high offices. These individuals are appointed to serve the [monarch](/Monarchy_of_Canada) and certain members of the extended [royal family](/Monarchy_of_Canada), the [governor general](/Governor_General_of_Canada), the various [lieutenant governors](/Lieutenant-Governor_(Canada)) of the provinces, and even specific other appointments such as the [Minister of National Defence](/Minister_of_National_Defence_(Canada)), [flag](/Flag_officer) and [general officers](/General_(Canada)), Canadian heads of mission abroad, and even foreign heads of state who are visiting Canada [5]. It seems no dignitary is left unattended.

Beyond the full-time military officers who serve as dedicated aides-de-camp to the governor general, a number of other flag, general, and senior officers are appointed *[ex officio](/Ex_officio)* as honorary aides-de-camp. These appointments extend to the governor general or even members of the royal family, signifying a broader, symbolic connection [5]. This distinguished list includes:

*   The [Chief of the Defence Staff](/Chief_of_the_Defence_Staff_(Canada)), the highest-ranking officer in the Canadian Forces.
*   The Commandant of the [Royal Military College of Canada](/Royal_Military_College_of_Canada), a pivotal figure in military education.
*   A senior officer specifically drawn from the Quebec-based Royal 22e Régiment, acknowledging its unique heritage.
*   The Commanding officer of [the Governor General's Horse Guards](/The_Governor_General%27s_Horse_Guards), a ceremonial cavalry regiment.
*   The Commanding officer of the [Governor General's Foot Guards](/Governor_General%27s_Foot_Guards), a prestigious infantry regiment.
*   The Commanding officer of [the Canadian Grenadier Guards](/The_Canadian_Grenadier_Guards), another distinguished infantry unit.
*   The Commanding officer of [the Queen's Own Rifles of Canada](/The_Queen%27s_Own_Rifles_of_Canada), with its own rich history.
*   And, rather specifically, the Commanding officers of [Naval Reserve](/Canadian_Forces_Primary_Reserve) divisions, ensuring representation across all branches.

Most aides-de-camp in Canada, when fulfilling their official duties, wear a distinctive gold-pattern [aiguillette](/Aiguillette). However, members of [St. John Ambulance Canada](/St._John_Ambulance_Canada) who serve in this capacity wear silver aiguillettes, consistent with their other accoutrements, a subtle but important distinction [citation needed]. Furthermore, all aides-de-camp are required to wear the cypher or badge of the principal they are appointed to serve [6], a clear visual indicator of their allegiance. Honorary appointees to the monarch, [King Charles III](/King_Charles_III), or the [Prince of Wales](/Prince_of_Wales), proudly display the appropriate cypher on their uniform epaulette and are entitled to use the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) ADC for the entire duration of their appointment, a permanent mark of temporary service.

Aides-de-camp to the governor general wear the governor general's specific badge, known as the crest of the [arms of Canada](/Arms_of_Canada), a symbol of national authority. Similarly, aides-de-camp to a lieutenant-governor wear the lieutenant-governor's badge, which typically features the shield of the province surmounted by a crown [6]. These appointments are exclusively made from officers of the [Canadian Forces](/Canadian_Forces). However, for lieutenant-governors, aides-de-camp can also be appointed from officers of the [Royal Canadian Mounted Police](/Royal_Canadian_Mounted_Police) and, depending on the specific provincial regulations, from other uniformed organizations such as municipal or provincial police forces and emergency services. In certain, presumably rare, instances, civilians may also be appointed. Non-uniformed civilians, understandably, do not wear the aiguillette, but they still display their lieutenant-governor's badge as a symbol of their appointment [6]. A notable development occurred on 29 November 1973, when Governor General [Roland Michener](/Roland_Michener) successfully concluded his initiative to permit aides-de-camp to the governor general and lieutenant-governors to use the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) A de C for the duration of their appointment [4] [7].

The wearing of the aiguillette itself is subject to strict protocol: aides-de-camp to royal and vice-regal personages wear the aiguillette on the right shoulder, a mark of direct service to the Crown. Aides-de-camp to all other principals, by contrast, wear their aiguillette on the left shoulder [6]. One must, it seems, know their left from their right when dealing with such matters.

### India

A rather formal scene unfolds on 28 August 2017, where a presidential aide-de-camp stands to the left of President [Ram Nath Kovind](/Ram_Nath_Kovind), who has just administered the oath of office to the newly appointed Indian [Chief Justice](/Chief_Justice_of_India), [Dipak Misra](/Dipak_Misra). Such moments underscore the gravity and formality of these roles.

In [India](/India), the structure of aide-de-camp appointments is extensive and deeply rooted in military tradition. Officers holding the rank of [major general](/Major_general) or its equivalent and above in the sister services, particularly those in command of divisions or peacetime commands, are typically assigned aides-de-camp. These aides usually hail from their general's parent regiment or battalion, fostering a sense of continuity and loyalty. There have even been documented instances where sons have served a tenure as aide-de-camp to their own fathers, a rather unique family tradition. In India, "aide-de-camp" is unequivocally considered a [title of honour](/Title_of_honour), and both current and former holders of this distinction are conferred the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letters) ADC, a lasting recognition of their service.

The service chiefs themselves — including the chief of the [Army](/Chief_of_the_Army_Staff_(India)), [Navy](/Chief_of_the_Naval_Staff_(India)), and [Air](/Chief_of_the_Air_Staff_(India)) Staff — are typically assigned three aides-de-camp. The [president of India](/President_of_India), as the supreme commander, is served by an even larger contingent of five aides-de-camp: three from the Army and one each from the Navy and the Air Force, ensuring balanced representation across the services. Additionally, there is one honorary aide-de-camp drawn from the [Territorial Army](/Territorial_Army_(India)). The president retains the prerogative to appoint any distinguished officer from the armed forces, including the service chiefs themselves, as an honorary aide-de-camp. The [governors](/Governor_(India)) of the various states are each served by two aides-de-camp: one from the [Indian Armed Forces](/Indian_Armed_Forces) and one from either the Indian or state police services. A notable exception to this rule is the state of [Jammu and Kashmir](/Jammu_and_Kashmir_(union_territory)), where both aides-de-camp to the governor are appointed exclusively from the [Indian Army](/Indian_Army), a reflection of the unique security considerations in that region.

### Malaysia

In [Malaysia](/Malaysia), the role of an aide-de-camp, locally known as *adikung*, is a formal appointment made either by the [federal government](/Federal_government_of_Malaysia) or by the individual [state governments](/State_governments_of_Malaysia). These appointments are typically drawn from officers of the [Royal Malaysian Police](/Royal_Malaysian_Police) or from the various components of the [Malaysian Armed Forces](/Malaysian_Armed_Forces), which include the [Malaysian Army](/Malaysian_Army), the [Royal Malaysian Air Force](/Royal_Malaysian_Air_Force), and the [Royal Malaysian Navy](/Royal_Malaysian_Navy). Interestingly, there have also been instances where individuals who are neither military personnel nor police officers have been appointed as aide-de-camp, suggesting a degree of flexibility in these prestigious roles.

### New Zealand

As is customary in other [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations) countries where the [monarch](/Monarchy_of_New_Zealand) still holds the position of head of state, personnel from the [New Zealand Defence Force](/New_Zealand_Defence_Force) are appointed to serve as aides-de-camp to royal and vice-regal personages. The governor-general of New Zealand, for instance, is served by two full-time aides-de-camp. These officers typically hold the rank of [army](/New_Zealand_Army) [captain](/Captain_(armed_forces)), [lieutenant](/Lieutenant_(navy)) in the [Royal New Zealand Navy](/Royal_New_Zealand_Navy) (RNZN), or [Royal New Zealand Air Force](/Royal_New_Zealand_Air_Force) (RNZAF) [flight lieutenant](/Flight_lieutenant). Additional and honorary aides-de-camp to the governor-general are usually of the rank of lieutenant colonel or its equivalent, signifying a higher level of seniority. The aiguillettes worn are of the standard palace No. 1 type, a rather specific designation, and are worn on the right shoulder, adhering to established protocol. Equivalent appointments also exist to serve the [minister of Defence](/Minister_of_Defence_(New_Zealand)), the [chief of Defence Force](/Chief_of_Defence_Force_(New_Zealand)), and the various service chiefs. These roles are typically known as military assistants (MA), personal staff officers (PSOs), or, in the case of the RNZN, flag lieutenants (flags). They wear service-specific No. 2 aiguillettes, distinguished by colored flecks – dark blue for navy, red for army, and light blue for air force – which are worn on the left shoulder, a rather meticulous system of differentiation.

### Pakistan

In [Pakistan](/Pakistan), the tradition of aides-de-camp is firmly established within the highest echelons of government and military leadership. The [president](/President_of_Pakistan), [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Pakistan), and provincial governors all have their own designated aides-de-camp. These aides can be drawn from any of the three [Armed Forces](/Pakistan_Armed_Forces) and typically hold the rank of [captain](/Captain_(land)) in the army, [lieutenant](/Lieutenant) in the navy, or [flight lieutenant](/Flight_lieutenant) in the air force, signifying a relatively junior but highly prestigious appointment. Historically, there have been notable instances of direct familial service, such as Captain Akhtar Munir Marwat serving as aide-de-camp to Justice [Khan Habibullah Khan](/Khan_Habibullah_Khan) when the latter was chief minister and leader of the house of [West Pakistan](/West_Pakistan). Similarly, Captain [Gohar Ayub Khan](/Gohar_Ayub_Khan) famously served his father, President Field Marshal [Ayub Khan](/Ayub_Khan_(Field_Marshal)), as an aide-de-camp. The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee and all three service chiefs are also authorized to have an aide-de-camp, ensuring comprehensive support at the highest levels. Furthermore, in Pakistan, officers holding the rank of major general and its equivalent and above in the sister services, particularly those in command of divisions or peacetime commands, are entitled to aides-de-camp, who usually belong to their general's parent regiment or battalion, maintaining a strong regimental connection.

### Papua New Guinea

As is the case in other [Commonwealth realms](/Commonwealth_realm) where the [monarch](/Monarchy_of_Papua_New_Guinea) remains the head of state, the governor-general of Papua New Guinea is served by two dedicated full-time aides-de-camp. One of these officers is drawn from the [Papua New Guinea Defence Force](/Papua_New_Guinea_Defence_Force), typically holding the rank of [PNGDF](/Papua_New_Guinea_Defence_Force) [captain](/Captain_(armed_forces)). The other aide is appointed from the [Royal Papua New Guinea Constabulary](/Royal_Papua_New_Guinea_Constabulary), holding the rank of [RPNGC](/Royal_Papua_New_Guinea_Constabulary) [superintendent](/Superintendent_(police)) [8]. This dual appointment reflects the importance of both military and civilian law enforcement in supporting the vice-regal office.

### Singapore

In [Singapore](/Singapore), the [president](/President_of_Singapore) carefully appoints aides-de-camp from three distinct uniformed services: the [Singapore Armed Forces](/Singapore_Armed_Forces) (SAF), the [Singapore Police Force](/Singapore_Police_Force) (SPF), and the [Singapore Civil Defence Force](/Singapore_Civil_Defence_Force) (SCDF). Officers selected from the SAF typically hold the rank of major or [military expert 5](/Singapore_Armed_Forces_ranks), while those from the SCDF usually hold the rank of major. SPF officers selected for these roles generally hold the rank of assistant superintendent of police. Notably, both male and female officers are eligible to serve as aides-de-camp, reflecting a commitment to gender inclusivity in these prestigious appointments.

Their duties are crucial and varied, encompassing the assistance in liaison for important guests on behalf of the president and the meticulous care of visiting foreign dignitaries [9]. They act as vital conduits and facilitators, ensuring the smooth execution of presidential engagements and the appropriate reception of international visitors.

### Sri Lanka

In [Sri Lanka](/Sri_Lanka), the [president](/President_of_Sri_Lanka) is served by a primary aide-de-camp and an extra aide-de-camp, both drawn from the three armed services, ensuring a balanced representation. Furthermore, all [general](/General_officer), [flag](/Flag_officer), and [air officers](/Air_officer) are entitled to an aide-de-camp, who is typically selected from their parent regiment or unit, reinforcing unit loyalty and familiarity. In the [Sri Lanka Navy](/Sri_Lanka_Navy), the equivalent position of an aide-de-camp is known as a flag lieutenant. Junior officers, specifically those holding the rank of major and below within the armed services, who have completed a minimum of three years of service, may be appointed for (extra-regimental) special appointments as an aide-de-camp or an extra aide-de-camp for a maximum tenure of three years. Following such an appointment, a reappointment is not permissible for a period of two years, ensuring a rotation of duties and opportunities [10]. Additionally, medical officers holding the rank of [lieutenant colonel](/Lieutenant_colonel) and above can be appointed as honorary physician to the president or honorary surgeon to the president, recognizing their specialized expertise at the highest level of state.

This tradition in Sri Lanka traces its origins back to the colonial era, specifically to the office of [governor of Ceylon](/Governors_of_British_Ceylon). The governor's staff historically included an aide-de-camp as a permanent appointment, drawing a salary from the civil list, and typically held by a retired junior officer from a British Army regiment. In a parallel but distinct role, the governor's staff also featured the [head mudaliyar](/Maha_Mudaliyar), who served as the native aide-de-camp to the governor on a permanent and honorary (non-paid) basis, representing indigenous leadership. Furthermore, several extra aides-de-camp were appointed from regiments of the [Ceylon Defense Force](/Ceylon_Defense_Force) and, later, from the [Ceylon Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve](/Sri_Lanka_Volunteer_Naval_Force). With the establishment of the office of the [Governor-General of Ceylon](/Governor-General_of_Ceylon) after independence, this practice continued, with Ceylon Army officers assuming the roles previously held by British Army officers. Presently, an officer holding the rank of brigadier serves as aide-de-camp to the president, while an officer of the rank of colonel or its equivalent serves as aide-de-camp to the defence secretary [11], demonstrating a clear chain of command and support.

The inherent dangers of such proximity to high-value targets have, tragically, been underscored by several incidents in Sri Lanka:

*   On 8 August 1992, [Major General](/Major_General) [Denzil Kobbekaduwa](/Denzil_Kobbekaduwa), who served as the [Overall Operations Commander - Northern Sector](/Security_Forces_Headquarters_%E2%80%93_Jaffna), and his aide-de-camp, Major Nalin S. De Alwis, were killed. This devastating loss occurred along with several other senior army and navy officers when their [Land Rover](/Land_Rover) struck a land mine off Araly Point in [Kayts](/Kayts) [12].
*   A few months later, on 16 November 1992, the [Commander of the Sri Lanka Navy](/Commander_of_the_Sri_Lanka_Navy), [Vice Admiral](/Vice_Admiral) [Clancy Fernando](/Clancy_Fernando), and his [flag lieutenant](/Flag_lieutenant), [Lieutenant](/Lieutenant) Sandun Gunasekera, were assassinated. This attack was carried out by an [LTTE](/LTTE) [suicide bomber](/Suicide_bomber) who deliberately drove an explosives-laden motorbike into the admiral's [staff car](/Staff_car) directly in front of the iconic [Galle Face Green](/Galle_Face_Green) [13].
*   More recently, in 2006, the [Commander of the Sri Lanka Army](/Commander_of_the_Sri_Lanka_Army), [Lieutenant General](/Lieutenant_General) [Sarath Fonseka](/Sarath_Fonseka), and his aide-de-camp, Major Priyal Wickramasinghe, were severely wounded. They were caught in an LTTE suicide bomb attack perpetrated by a pregnant LTTE operative who targeted the general's staff car inside the heavily guarded [Army Headquarters](/Army_Headquarters,_Colombo) [14] [15] [16]. These incidents serve as stark reminders of the constant threat faced by those in these critical support roles.

### Tanzania

A photograph from May 2009 captures [Jakaya Kikwete](/Jakaya_Kikwete), then [president of Tanzania](/President_of_Tanzania), with his aide-de-camp (positioned on the right) at the [Walter Reed Army Research Institute](/Walter_Reed_Army_Medical_Center), a scene that could be anywhere, yet is specific.

The [president of Tanzania](/President_of_Tanzania) is served by an aide-de-camp drawn from the [Tanzania People's Defence Force](/Tanzania_People%27s_Defence_Force). This individual typically holds the rank of *kanali*, which is the equivalent of a [colonel](/Colonel) in other military systems, signifying a senior and experienced officer.

## United Kingdom

### Historic usage

General Sir [Baker Russell](/Baker_Russell) is depicted in his full-dress uniform, specifically that of an aide-de-camp to [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria), a rather elaborate ensemble for what was, at its core, a functional role.

In the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), the role of an aide-de-camp (ADC) was rather clearly defined in 1875 as "a confidential officer attached to the 'personal' or private staff of a [general](/General)" [17]. Their duties, much like the general's temperament, varied depending on the circumstances. In the unforgiving environment of the [field of battle](/Field_of_battle), the aide-de-camp functioned as "the bearer of his chief's written or verbal orders, and when employed as the general's mouthpiece must be implicitly obeyed" [17]. Their word, in essence, was the general's word, a weighty responsibility. However, when in garrison or more settled quarters, their duties took on a decidedly more social character: "he superintends the general's household, writes and answers invitations, &c." [17]. It seems even generals, then as now, required assistance with their social calendars. Historically, this appointment was exclusively within the Army; in the Navy, a flag lieutenant performed equivalent duties, primarily "communicating the admiral's orders to the various ships either personally or by signal" [18], a more direct, nautical form of communication.

According to a British military dictionary published in 1816, an ADC generally held a rank equal to, or even more senior than, an [army captain](/Army_captain). The number of aides-de-camp a general was entitled to was directly proportional to their rank: "Generals, being [field marshals](/Field_marshal) have four [aides-de-camp], [lieutenant generals](/Lieutenant_general) two, [and] [major generals](/Major_general) one" [19]. A clear hierarchy, even in personal assistance.

The sovereign, in their capacity as [head of the army](/Head_of_the_British_Armed_Forces), held the prerogative to appoint "an indefinite number of aides-de-camp" [17]. During the reign of [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria), appointments were typically made (drawing officers from both the regular Army and the [Royal Marines](/Royal_Marines)) as a recognition of distinguished service in wartime. This appointment, at that time, notably carried with it an automatic promotion to the rank of [full colonel](/Colonel_(United_Kingdom)), a significant career advancement. Additional honorary appointments were also made from among the officers of the [Militia](/Militia_(United_Kingdom)), and Queen Victoria also saw fit to appoint a number of "naval aides-de-camp" as a "compliment to the sister service" [17], fostering inter-service goodwill.

Colonial [governors](/Governor), [governors-general](/Governors-general), and even the [lord lieutenant of Ireland](/Lord_lieutenant_of_Ireland) [2] also made their own appointments of aides-de-camp. These individuals often fulfilled a functional role quite similar to that of [equerries](/Equerry) within the [Royal Household](/Royal_Households_of_the_United_Kingdom), where, by contrast, aides-de-camp typically hold a primarily honorific role [17]. It's a subtle distinction, but one with implications for daily duties.

Historically, army aides-de-camp were distinguished by a truly distinctive and rather elaborate [full dress uniform](/Full_dress_uniform). However, the practicalities of modern warfare and perhaps a general decline in ostentation led to its use being largely discontinued after [World War I](/World_War_I), a quiet concession to efficiency.

### Present day

In the contemporary [British Army](/British_Army) and the [Royal Air Force](/RAF), a junior officer may still be appointed to serve as aide-de-camp to a senior officer, providing direct support and assistance. The equivalent appointment within the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) is, rather predictably, that of flag lieutenant, carrying similar responsibilities within a naval context. Furthermore, certain representatives of the monarch, such as the [lord-lieutenants](/Lord-lieutenant) of counties, retain the authority to appoint their own aides-de-camp [20], extending the tradition to regional civic roles.

### The Royal Household

Beyond these functional roles, a specific, fixed number of senior officers hold appointments as aides-de-camp directly to the monarch. This highly prestigious appointment confers upon the holder the right to use the [post-nominal letters](/Post-nominal_letter) "ADC." The majority of these are serving officers from the army, navy, and air force, typically holding the rank of colonel or brigadier, or their naval and air force equivalents. While the appointment is highly honorific, they are seldom called upon individually to perform specific, day-to-day duties. However, collectively, they play a visible role in significant state occasions, having walked in procession at every [coronation](/Coronation_of_the_British_monarch) and [state funeral](/State_funerals_in_the_United_Kingdom) of a monarch throughout the 20th century [21], a silent testament to enduring tradition. As of 1991, the aides-de-camp to the queen numbered precisely sixty, a rather specific roster: [22]

*   Eight officers from the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy), holding the ranks of captain and commodore.
*   Three officers from the [Royal Naval Reserve](/Royal_Naval_Reserve), representing the volunteer element.
*   One officer from the [Royal Marines](/Royal_Marines), holding the rank of colonel, acknowledging their distinct service.
*   One officer from the [Royal Marines Reserve](/Royal_Marines_Reserve), further representing reserve forces.
*   Eighteen officers from the Army, all holding the rank of brigadier.
*   Sixteen officers from the [Territorial Army](/Territorial_Army_(UK)), holding the rank of colonel, demonstrating the integration of reserve components.
*   Twelve officers from the [Royal Air Force](/RAF), holding the rank of air commodore or group captain.
*   One officer from the [Royal Auxiliary Air Force](/Royal_Auxiliary_Air_Force) or the [Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve](/Royal_Air_Force_Volunteer_Reserve), ensuring representation from the RAF's reserve elements.

In addition to this broader group, there are specific, even more senior aide-de-camp appointments held by certain very high-ranking officers, whose roles carry even greater weight and visibility. These include:

*   The [first and principal naval aide-de-camp](/List_of_First_and_Principal_Naval_Aides-de-Camp), a singular, distinguished naval appointment.
*   The [flag aide-de-camp](/List_of_First_and_Principal_Naval_Aides-de-Camp), another specific naval role.
*   The [aide-de-camp general](/Aide-de-camp_general), a senior army appointment.
*   The [air aide-de-camp](/Air_aide-de-camp), a similar high-ranking position within the Royal Air Force.

These distinguished individuals are collectively known as the principal aides-de-camp. The first two listed are individual naval appointments of significant seniority. During the reign of Queen Elizabeth II, there were typically up to three aides-de-camp general ("ADC(Gen)") appointed from the most senior ranks of the British Army, with one of these often being the [chief of the General Staff](/Chief_of_the_General_Staff_(United_Kingdom)) himself. Similarly, up to two air aides-de-camp were appointed from among the senior ranks of the RAF, one of whom was usually the [chief of the Air Staff](/Chief_of_the_Air_Staff_(United_Kingdom)) [22].

The principal aides-de-camp, by virtue of their high office and representing the three services, play a prominent role alongside other members of the Royal Household in the elaborate [State Processions](/State_Procession_at_the_State_Opening_of_Parliament) at [State Openings of Parliament](/State_Openings_of_Parliament), at coronations, and at state funerals. They are also occasionally called upon individually to represent the monarch at memorial services and other significant public occasions [22], embodying the monarch's presence where the sovereign cannot be.

### Uniform accoutrements

Aides-de-camp, much like [equerries](/Equerry), [military assistants](/Military_assistant), [military attachés](/Military_attach%C3%A9), and certain other officers, are distinguished by the addition of [aiguillettes](/Aiguillettes) to their dress uniforms. These elaborate braided cords are not uniform across all appointments; they differ in size, color, and prescribed position of wear, depending on the specific role [20], a testament to the intricate world of military protocol. Furthermore, aides-de-camp to the sovereign wear the monarch's unique [royal cypher](/Royal_cypher) prominently on their shoulder straps or shoulder boards, visible in various orders of dress, a direct link to the Crown.

In the particularly distinguished cases of [personal aide-de-camp](/Personal_aide-de-camp) to the monarch and the principal aides-de-camp, the officers concerned are permitted to continue wearing the royal cypher even after they have relinquished their appointment, a rare and lasting mark of honor. Should an officer have held the appointment under more than one sovereign, the cypher of each monarch is worn, creating a chronological display of service [23] [24]. In all other instances, an officer is expected to cease wearing these accoutrements once their appointment as aide-de-camp is relinquished, with the sole exception that former aides-de-camp to the sovereign appointed before 1988 may also continue to wear the royal cypher [20]. Such are the precise, and sometimes rather arbitrary, rules of tradition.

## France

