In [France](/France), the president, by virtue of his position as [commander-in-chief](/Commander-in-chief) of the [French Armed Forces](/French_Armed_Forces), is served by a dedicated team of aides-de-camp. Generally, there are three such officers, traditionally including at least one member of the [French Army](/French_Army), and all of whom typically hold the rank of [lieutenant colonel](/Lieutenant_colonel). Their primary, and arguably most chilling, mission is to transport the [briefcase](/Nuclear_briefcase) that contains the codes and protocols permitting the use of [nuclear weapons](/Nuclear_weapon), a constant reminder of the ultimate responsibility. Beyond this rather weighty task, they also provide more general assistance to the president. For instance, aides-de-camp are often observed placing the president's speech on his lectern just as he arrives, or discreetly holding up [cue cards](/Cue_card) for the president during award ceremonies, ensuring a smooth public appearance.

When the president undertakes travel, an aide-de-camp almost invariably occupies the front passenger seat of the presidential car. This positioning ensures they are among the individuals physically closest to the president at all times, a constant presence and a direct line of support, or indeed, defense.

## Greece

