The [President of the Hellenic Republic](/President_of_Greece), in their esteemed capacity as Head of State of the [Hellenic Armed Forces](/Hellenic_Armed_Forces), is served by a dedicated team of aides-de-camp. These officers are drawn from the three primary branches of the Greek military: the [Hellenic Air Force](/Hellenic_Air_Force), the [Hellenic Navy](/Hellenic_Navy), and the [Hellenic Army](/Hellenic_Army), ensuring comprehensive representation and expertise across the services.

## Hong Kong

This section, much like a bureaucratic filing cabinet, needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Should you possess a sudden urge to contribute, please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Aide-de-camp) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners) in this section. Otherwise, this unsourced material may be challenged and, predictably, removed. Find sources: "Aide-de-camp" – news · newspapers · books · scholar · JSTOR (October 2022). One might also consider [Learning how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal).

In [Hong Kong](/Hong_Kong), a diverse array of uniformed services each despatches an aide-de-camp to serve the territory's chief executive, who assumed the role previously held by the governor in 1997. This impressive roster of contributing departments includes the Hong Kong Police Force, the Fire Services Department, the Customs and Excise Department, the Immigration Department, the Government Flying Service, the Civil Aid Service, the Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force, the Auxiliary Medical Service, the St. John Ambulance Brigade, and the Correctional Services Department, demonstrating a broad spectrum of state support.

A particularly poignant and historically charged moment occurred on the very last day of British rule in Hong Kong, 30 June 1997. The [police](/Royal_Hong_Kong_Police) aide-de-camp to Governor [Chris Patten](/Chris_Patten) performed a final, symbolic duty: he presented Patten with the flag at [Government House](/Government_House,_Hong_Kong). Following this, he rendered the [Vice Regal Salute](/Vice_Regal_Salute), a final act of colonial deference, before proceeding, alongside the Pattens, to leave Government House for the very last time, marking the end of an era.

## Imperial Russia

In the grand, often theatrical, courts of 18th-century [Russia](/Russia), under the formidable reign of [Catherine the Great](/Catherine_the_Great), the appointment of aides-de-camp was not merely a matter of military efficiency. Favorites of the Empress were, with rather predictable frequency, appointed to these coveted positions, a testament to the intricate interplay of power, politics, and personal influence within the imperial court.

Later, during the tumultuous period of [World War I](/World_War_I), distinguished officers were appointed as the [Emperor's](/Emperor_of_Russia) aide-de-camp on a rotating basis, a system designed to honor meritorious service and perhaps to share the burden of proximity to the increasingly embattled throne. In November 1916, for instance, the future [Civil War](/Russian_Civil_War) [White Army](/White_Army) general [Pyotr Wrangel](/Pyotr_Wrangel), who at that time commanded a [regiment](/Regiment), spent a few days serving as an aide-de-camp for [Nicholas II of Russia](/Nicholas_II_of_Russia) [25], a fleeting glimpse into the inner circle of a doomed dynasty.

## Indonesia

A rather formal tableau from August 2017 captures the presidential aide-de-camps standing diligently behind [Indonesian President](/President_of_Indonesia) [Joko Widodo](/Joko_Widodo) as he delivers his presidential speech to the Indonesian Parliament, known as the [People's Consultative Assembly](/People%27s_Consultative_Assembly). Their presence is a constant, subtle assertion of presidential authority and security.

In [Indonesia](/Indonesia), an aide-de-camp, locally referred to as an *ajudan presiden* or "president's adjutant," serves both the [president](/President_of_Indonesia) and [vice president](/Vice_President_of_Indonesia) of Indonesia. These crucial support roles are filled by [officers](/Officer_(armed_forces)) drawn from the [Indonesian National Armed Forces](/Indonesian_National_Armed_Forces), typically holding the rank of [colonel](/Colonel), and/or the [Indonesian National Police](/Indonesian_National_Police), where they hold the rank of [Police Chief Commissioner](/Indonesian_National_Police). Their comprehensive mandate includes providing essential staff support and daily administrative services to the president and vice president, as well as to their respective spouses, whether these duties pertain to official capacities or more personal affairs [26] [27]. They are, rather conspicuously, recognized by their gleaming golden [aiguillettes](/Aiguillette), a clear mark of their esteemed position.

Beyond the presidential and vice-presidential offices, other [VIPs](/VIP) in Indonesia, such as government ministers and other important officials, are also provided with ADCs. These aides are typically junior-ranking officers, often [lieutenants](/Lieutenants) in the military or police inspectors from the police, who are generally recent graduates from the [military](/Indonesian_Military_Academy) and/or [police](/Police_academy) academies, providing them with invaluable early career experience. For regional officials, such as [governors](/Governors) and [mayors](/Mayors) (including those known as [Regents](/Kabupaten)), ADCs are provided from the ranks of new graduates of the Institute of Domestic Governance (IPDN), ensuring a steady supply of trained personnel for these vital support roles.

## Ireland

The [president of Ireland](/President_of_Ireland), in their capacity as supreme commander of the [Irish Defence Forces](/Defence_Forces_(Ireland)), is served by a dedicated group of aides-de-camp. These officers play a multifaceted role, assisting with the day-to-day presidential duties, accompanying the president on official public engagements both within Ireland and during [state visits](/State_visit) abroad, and representing the president at funerals and other significant state occasions. Their commitment is unwavering, as an ADC is on duty 24 hours a day, seven days a week, at [Áras an Uachtaráin](/%C3%81ras_an_Uachtar%C3%A1in), the official residence of the president [28].

Historically, the role of an aide-de-camp has been one of both personal service and close protection. A notable figure from Irish history, [Michael Collins](/Michael_Collins_(Irish_Leader)), served in this very capacity, acting as both aide-de-camp and bodyguard to [Joseph Plunkett](/Joseph_Plunkett) during the pivotal Easter Rising in 1916. A stark reminder that such roles often place individuals at the very heart of historical events.

## Japan

### Main article: [Aide-de-camp to the Emperor of Japan](/Aide-de-camp_to_the_Emperor_of_Japan)

From 1896 until the devastating conclusion of [World War II](/World_War_II), the [emperors of Japan](/Emperor_of_Japan) maintained a distinct cadre of both army and naval aides-de-camp, reflecting the dual nature of their imperial military command.

## Portugal

The president of Portugal, in their paramount role as [commander-in-chief](/Commander-in-chief) of the Portuguese armed forces, is supported by three dedicated aides-de-camp. These officers are carefully selected, with one each drawn from the [Portuguese Army](/Portuguese_Army), the [Portuguese Navy](/Portuguese_Navy), and the [Portuguese Air Force](/Portuguese_Air_Force), ensuring a balanced representation of the nation's military might. These aides-de-camp are integral members of the Presidential Military Household, operating in close coordination with the highest office [29] [30]. A notable aspect of their service is the strict tenure: Portuguese aides-de-camp are never permitted to serve for more than one presidential term, which in Portugal is five years in duration. After this period, they return to their respective branches of the armed forces [29], ensuring a regular rotation of personnel and fresh perspectives.

## Serbia

In the historical landscape of the [Principality of Serbia](/Principality_of_Serbia) and subsequently the [Kingdom of Serbia](/Kingdom_of_Serbia), the Monarch's Aide-de-Camp held a truly pivotal position, effectively serving as a crucial bridge between the monarchy and the nation's military affairs. This role was far from merely ceremonial; it encompassed a broad spectrum of critical responsibilities vital to national defense. These aides-de-camp were instrumental in advising the monarch on intricate military strategy, overseeing the armament and rigorous training of the armed forces, and providing indispensable support during delicate diplomatic engagements [31]. They were, in essence, the monarch's eyes and ears within the military establishment, ensuring that royal directives were understood and implemented, and that the military's needs and capabilities were accurately conveyed to the crown.

The aides-de-camp provided invaluable, indeed indispensable, assistance to the monarchy in managing the often complex and sensitive state and military matters of the realm. Their presence ensured smooth coordination with the armed forces, preventing potential communication breakdowns or strategic misalignments. Beyond their practical functions, through the diligent performance of their duties, Serbian monarch aides-de-camp embodied royal dignity, leading ceremonial functions at court with grace and precision. They stood as enduring symbols of the monarchy’s authority and stability [31], their very presence projecting the strength and continuity of the state.

## Spain

In Spain, the [Royal Household](/Royal_Household_of_Spain) maintains, within the King's Military Chamber or Military Staff, an unspecified number of aides-de-camp. This structure is governed by Royal Decree 434/1988, issued on May 6, with its current wording updated by Royal Decree 772/2015 on August 28. Prior to the 2015 reform, there were specifically 10 aides serving the King, along with an unspecified number for the [Prince of Asturias](/Prince_of_Asturias) [32]. However, since the August 2015 reform, the precise number of assistants is no longer explicitly specified, though it is stipulated that they must hold military ranks of [commander](/Commander) or [corvette captain](/Corvette_captain) (equivalent to [OF-3](/OF-3)), [lieutenant colonel](/Lieutenant_colonel) or [frigate captain](/Frigate_captain) (OF-4), or [colonel](/Colonel) or [ship-of-the-line captain](/Ship-of-the-line_captain) (OF-5). Furthermore, the requirement that the first assistant must hold the rank of [general](/General) (OF-6 or higher) is maintained, as this individual also serves as the head of the King's Military Chamber, a position of significant command [32].

As of 2025, the King of Spain is served by nine aides-de-camp (this count excludes the first aide). These nine officers are drawn from various branches of the armed forces and security services: four from the [Spanish Army](/Spanish_Army), two from the [Spanish Navy](/Spanish_Navy), two from the [Spanish Air and Space Force](/Spanish_Air_and_Space_Force), and one from the [Civil Guard](/Civil_Guard_(Spain)) [33] [34]. These aides operate on a continuous rotational basis, taking turns 24 hours a day, every single day of the year [35], ensuring constant support and availability to the monarch.

## Thailand

A photograph from March 1950 captures a Royal aide-de-camp (prominently in the center) participating in the ceremonial progress for the royal funeral of King [Ananda Mahidol](/Ananda_Mahidol) of [Thailand](/Thailand), a solemn and intricate display of respect and tradition.

The Royal Thai Aide-De-Camp Department is a specialized royal service agency operating under the larger umbrella of the [Royal Security Command](/Royal_Security_Command). Its responsibilities are crucial to the functioning and public image of the monarchy: it is primarily tasked with meticulously organizing royal appearances and ensuring the comprehensive safety and security of the [Thai royal family](/Thai_royal_family). Beyond these central duties, Royal Thai aides-de-camp are also appointed to serve senior officers of the Thai [Army](/Royal_Thai_Army), [Navy](/Royal_Thai_Navy), and [Air Force](/Royal_Thai_Air_Force), extending their support to the broader military leadership. The origins of this system can be traced back to [King Chulalongkorn](/King_Chulalongkorn), who initiated the Royal Guard in 1870 during his visit to Singapore and Indonesia. He was accompanied by a lieutenant general who served as his personal aide, and this individual is historically regarded as the very first Thai aide-de-camp [36], marking the beginning of a long-standing tradition.

## United States

[U.S. Navy](/United_States_Navy) Captain A. S. McDill (visible in the left rear), who served as aide-de-camp to Fleet Admiral [Ernest J. King](/Ernest_J._King), is captured in a historical photograph at the [Potsdam Conference](/Potsdam_Conference) in April 1945, a stark reminder of the global significance of these roles. Another image, from March 2020, shows an aide-de-camp diligently holding a [brigadier general's](/Brigadier_general) flag as a U.S. general [37] unfurls it, a small but significant act in military protocol.

Within the United States, military officers are specifically assigned to serve as aides to a number of very high-ranking government officials. This includes the [Secretary of the Army](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Army), the [Secretary of Defense](/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense), the [vice president](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States), and, of course, the [president of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States). For government officials who have the luxury of more than one aide, the senior-ranking aide typically assumes the crucial role of coordinating the activities of the other aides, as well as managing personal attendants such as drivers or [orderlies](/Batman_(military)) [38], ensuring a seamless flow of support.

The president of the United States is served by a highly select group of six military aides, with one officer drawn from each of the armed services. The president's aides from the Army, Marine Corps, Air Force, and Space Force typically hold the ranks of [majors](/Major_(United_States)) or [lieutenant colonels](/Lieutenant_colonel_(United_States)), while the aides from the Navy and Coast Guard are generally [lieutenant commanders](/Lieutenant_commander_(United_States)) or [commanders](/Commander_(United_States)). One of their most critical, and indeed globally significant, roles is to carry the presidential [nuclear football](/Nuclear_football), a chillingly direct link to the nation's ultimate power. In addition to these six permanent aides-de-camp, there are approximately 40 to 45 [military social aides](/White_House_social_aides) who hold more junior ranks, ranging from [lieutenant](/Lieutenant_(United_States)) to major. Their appointments are temporary and part-time, typically serving for perhaps two to four afternoons a month as required, primarily for social purposes such as gatherings hosted at the [White House](/White_House) [citation needed] [39], a somewhat less existential duty.

In the [United States Army](/United_States_Army), aides-de-camp are specifically appointed to [general](/General_officers_in_the_United_States)-grade officers, encompassing the [NATO Code](/Ranks_and_insignia_of_NATO) ranks from [OF-6](/One-star_rank) through [OF-10](/Five-star_rank). The typical tour of duty for these aides is generally up to two years [citation needed], providing a structured rotation of personnel. While Congress has authorized general officers to be assigned up to three officer aides, with their number and rank contingent upon the general's grade, Army regulations have, perhaps pragmatically, traditionally limited each general to a single officer aide [39] [38]. Some generals are also authorized to have enlisted aides on their staff [40], providing additional support. A general, based on their specific grade, has the prerogative to choose a commissioned officer for an aide-de-camp up to the following maximum ranks: [39]

*   For a [Brigadier general](/Brigadier_general_(United_States)), the aide may be a [first lieutenant](/First_lieutenant).
*   For a [Major general](/Major_general_(United_States)), the aide may be a [captain](/Captain_(United_States_O-3)).
*   For a [Lieutenant general](/Lieutenant_general_(United_States)), the aide may be a [major](/Major_(United_States)).
*   For a [General](/General_(United_States)), the aide may be a [lieutenant colonel](/Lieutenant_colonel_(United_States)).
*   The [Chief of Staff, U.S. Army](/Chief_of_Staff_of_the_United_States_Army), is authorized a lieutenant colonel as aide, and also four enlisted aides [41].
*   A [General of the army](/General_of_the_Army_(United_States)), a rare and highest rank, is authorized a lieutenant colonel as aide, and three enlisted aides [38].

It is worth noting that lieutenant colonels and colonels who are in command of units (battalions and brigades, respectively) are not typically authorized aides. Occasionally, the unit's [adjutant](/Adjutant) ([S1](/S1_(military))) might assist the commanding officer in an aide-like capacity, but this practice is uncommon and not a formal aide-de-camp role. A general of the army, by virtue of their unique status, does not retire in the conventional sense and remains an officer of the United States Army for life [42], and thus is permanently entitled to an aide.

[U.S. Army](/United_States_Army) aides-de-camp are distinguished by wearing a special device, rather than the standard [branch-of-service](/United_States_Army_branch_insignia) insignia (representing infantry, artillery, or quartermaster, for example) that they would otherwise display on the lapels of their service uniform. This unique device indicates the rank of the general officer being served, as illustrated below. While the chief of staff of the Army and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff both hold O-10 positions, their aides-de-camp wear devices specific to those particular high offices, rather than the generic four-star aide device. Additionally, an aide-de-camp wears a special [aiguillette](/Aiguillette) on the shoulder of their dress uniform, a further mark of their distinctive role.

*   Insignia for an aide to a brigadier general
*   Insignia for an aide to a major general
*   Insignia for an aide to a lieutenant general
*   Insignia for an aide to a general
*   Insignia for an aide to a [general of the army](/General_of_the_Army_(United_States)) (a rather historical note, as the most recent general of the army retired from active service in 1953)
*   Insignia for an aide to the vice chief of staff of the army
*   Insignia for an aide to the chief of staff of the army
*   Insignia for an aide to the under secretary of the army
*   Insignia for an aide to the secretary of the army
*   Insignia for an aide to the vice chief of the National Guard Bureau
*   Insignia for an aide to the chief of the National Guard Bureau
*   Insignia for an aide to the vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
*   Insignia for an aide to the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
*   Insignia for an aide to the secretary of Defense
*   Insignia for an aide to the vice president of the United States
*   Insignia for an aide to the president of the United States

In the [U.S. Navy](/United_States_Navy), the aide-de-camp to an [admiral](/Admiral_(United_States)) is also known by specific maritime designations: a "flag aide" when serving a command ashore, or a "flag lieutenant" when serving a command afloat [43] [44], maintaining distinct terminology for naval operations.

The state of [Tennessee](/Tennessee) in the U.S. confers its highest honor, the title of "Colonel Aide de Camp." These colonels serve as the personal aides-de-camp to the [governor of Tennessee](/Governor_of_Tennessee), and their appointments are meticulously recorded by the [Secretary of State of Tennessee](/Secretary_of_State_of_Tennessee) alongside those who have been commissioned into the State Guard and [Tennessee National Guard](/Tennessee_National_Guard) [45], ensuring a formal and documented recognition of their service.

